{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488864"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:00:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:00:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"561"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/561"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.28,0.08,0.25,0.39]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"561"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75712"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/561"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"561"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61230"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"3714"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4979"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6527"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6614"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17182"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23649"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75712"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the ward review on day four post elective right total hip arthroplasty. His operation was uneventful. He has been receiving prophylactic unfractionated heparin post-operatively. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has developed intense right calf pain. He denies chest pain or dyspnoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His right calf is swollen and tender.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin 130 g/L (115-155)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelets 30 x 10^9/L (150-450)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count 10.2 x 10^9/L (4.0-10.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EActivated partial thromboplastin time 60 seconds (24-38)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHeparin-induced thrombocytopaenia is suspected.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate alternative anticoagulant after cessation of heparin?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prophylactic heparin","Enoxaparin","Dalteparin","Warfarin","Danaparoid"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of heparin-induced thrombocytopaenia (HIT): a significant drop in platelet count and new thrombosis (calf pain suggesting deep vein thrombosis) following heparin exposure. The timing of 4 days post-operatively is typical, as HIT usually develops 5-10 days after starting heparin, or earlier in patients with recent heparin exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe first step in management, without waiting for testing result, is immediate cessation of all forms of heparin. In addition, a non-heparin anticoagulant needs to be commenced. \u003Cstrong\u003EDanaparoid\u003C/strong\u003E is an option. It works by inhibiting factor Xa and IIa via antithrombin. It is administered via a continuous intravenous infusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProphylactic heparin\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0and other heparin products, including\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Eenoxaparin\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0and\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Edalteparin,\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0are absolutely contraindicated as they can worsen HIT. There is significant cross-reactivity between unfractionated heparin and low molecular weight heparins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E monotherapy is contraindicated in acute HIT as it can paradoxically worsen thrombosis through protein C depletion. It should only be commenced once the platelet count has recovered (\u0026gt;150 x 10^9/L) and after initial treatment with a parenteral non-heparin anticoagulant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther alternative anticoagulants that may be used include argatroban, bivalirudin, and fondaparinux. The choice depends on local availability, renal function, and hepatic function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["All forms of heparin must be immediately discontinued if HIT is suspected, without waiting for confirmatory testing.","In addition, a non-heparin anticoagulant needs to be commenced. Options include danaparoid, fondaparinux, argatroban, and bivalirudin."],"references":["Cuker A, Arepally GM, Chong BH, et al. American Society of Hematology 2018 guidelines for management of venous thromboembolism: heparin-induced thrombocytopenia. Blood Adv. 2018;2(22):3360-3392. doi:10.1182/bloodadvances.2018024489","Joseph J, Rabbolini D, Enjeti AK, et al. Diagnosis and management of heparin-induced thrombocytopenia: a consensus statement from the Thrombosis and Haemostasis Society of Australia and New Zealand HIT Writing Group. Med J Aust. 2019;210(11):509-516. doi:10.5694/mja2.50213","Ng JY, D\u0027Souza M, Hutani F, Choi P. Management of Heparin-Induced Thrombocytopenia: A Contemporary Review. J Clin Med. 2024;13(16):4686. Published 2024 Aug 9. doi:10.3390/jcm13164686"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61230"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"561"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61230"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T19:49:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-31T22:57:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"561"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75712"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"3714","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3714"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Heparin-induced thrombocytopaenia","synonyms":["HIT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-09-23T21:59:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-25T11:54:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"contributions","id":"4979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/contributions/4979"},"attributes":{"finalizedAt":"2022-07-24T09:07:56+09:30","userDetails":{"name":"Kassem Abdulsater","title":"Dr","isExpert":false,"